  "text": "Can these disparities be explained at the molecular level? One of the two intercalating amino acids between the inner active-site cysteines in Ero1a and Ero1b is different (Fig. 4) . When mutated to the Ero1b active-site sequence, the catalytic turnover number of Ero1a increases [CITATION_1] . Moreover, Ero1b harbors an additional cysteine at position 262 (Fig. 4) , which has been proposed to form a unique type of regulatory disulfide together with Cys 100 [CITATION_2] . However, as predictable by homology to Ero1a, Cys 262 is located at the end of one of the ",
